      {
        "para_id": "p35",
        "section_heading": "4.2 Computational Surjectivity",
        "text": "In general, we have no guarantees on the structure of FP and so peers must prove in zero knowledge that vi is the result of a valid computation of FP (Figure 3, step 5). But if FP is computationally surjective, then all possible vi \u2208 V are implicitly the output of some computation of FP . Thus, it only becomes necessary to prove that the shares of each peers\u2019 input reconstructs a point within V .",
        "seg_type": "par"
      },
